# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apdex-score
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apdex-score/apdex] When engaging in application performance management, for example in the course of website monitoring, enterprises collect many measurements of the performance of information technology applications.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] However, this measurement data may not provide a clear and simple picture of how well those applications are performing from a business point of view, a characteristic desired in metrics that are used as key performance indicators.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] Reporting several different kinds of data can confuse.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] Reducing measurement data to a single well understood metric is a convenient way to track and report on quality of experience.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] The Apdex method seeks to address these problems.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] Proponents of the Apdex standard believe that it offers a better way to "measure what matters".
[src:apdex-score/apdex] The Apdex method converts many measurements into one number on a uniform scale of 0 to 1 (0 = no users satisfied, 1 = all users satisfied).
[src:apdex-score/apdex] The resulting Apdex score is a numerical measure of user satisfaction with the performance of enterprise applications.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] This metric can be used to report on any source of end-user performance measurements for which a performance objective has been defined.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] where the sub-script t is the target time, and the tolerable time is assumed to be 4 times the target time.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] So it is easy to see how this ratio is always directly related to users' perceptions of satisfactory application responsiveness.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] The Apdex formula is equivalent to a weighted average, where a satisfied user is given a score of 1, a tolerating user is given a score of 0.5, and a frustrated user is given a score of 0.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] The Apdex Alliance, headquartered in Charlottesville, Virginia, was founded in 2004 by Peter Sevcik, President of NetForecast, Inc.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] The Alliance is a group of companies that are collaborating to establish the Apdex standard.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] These companies have perceived the need for a simple and uniform way to report on application performance, are adopting the Apdex method in their internal operations or software products, and are participating in the work of refining and extending the definition of the Apdex specifications.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] Alliance contributing members who incorporate the standard into their products may use the Apdex name or logo where the Alliance has certified them as compliant.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] In January 2007, the Alliance comprised 11 contributing member companies, and over 200 individual members.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] While the number of contributing companies has remained relatively stable, individual membership grew to over 800 by December 2008, and reached 2000 in 2010.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] In 2008 the Alliance began publishing a blog, the Apdex Exchange, and in 2010, began offering educational Webinars.
[src:apdex-score/apdex] These activities address performance management topics, with an emphasis on how to apply the Apdex methodology.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] In the fields of information technology and systems management, **application performance management** (**APM**) is the monitoring and management of the performance and availability of software applications.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] APM strives to detect and diagnose complex application performance problems to maintain an expected level of service.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] The term monitoring was replaced by many tool vendors by the term Observability.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Often, monitoring is seen as the technical process of data collection, whereas observability is seen as the capability to understand a systems behavior.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Two sets of performance metrics are closely monitored.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] The first set of performance metrics defines the performance experienced by end-users of the application.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] One example of performance is average response times under peak load.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] The second set of performance metrics measures the computational resources used by the application for the load, indicating whether there is adequate capacity to support the load, as well as possible locations of a performance bottleneck.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Measurement of these quantities establishes an empirical performance baseline for the application.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] The baseline can then be used to detect changes in performance.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Changes in performance can be correlated with external events and subsequently used to predict future changes in application performance.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] The use of APM is common for Web applications, which lends itself best to the more detailed monitoring techniques.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] In addition to measuring response time for a user, response times for components of a Web application can also be monitored to help pinpoint causes of delay.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] There also exist HTTP appliances that can decode transaction-specific response times at the Web server layer of the application.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Measuring application performance causes overhead, that might also influence the user experience.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] The overhead can be reduced by several technical measures, including reducing the amount of monitored events and aggregation of data before serialization.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Since the first half of 2013, APM has entered into a period of intense competition in technology and strategy with a multiplicity of vendors and viewpoints.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] This has caused an upheaval in the marketplace with vendors from unrelated backgrounds (including network monitoring, systems management, application instrumentation, and web performance monitoring) adopting messaging around APM.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] As a result, the term APM has become diluted and has evolved into a concept for managing application performance across many diverse computing platforms, rather than a single market.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] With so many vendors to choose from, selecting one can be a challenge.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] It is important to evaluate each carefully to ensure its capabilities meet your needs.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Two challenges for implementing APM are (1) it can be difficult to instrument an application to monitor application performance, especially among components of an application, and (2) applications can be virtualized, which increases the variability of the measurements.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] To alleviate the first problem application service management (ASM) provides an application-centric approach, where business service performance visibility is a key objective.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] The second aspect present in distributed, virtual and cloud-based applications poses a unique challenge for application performance monitoring because most of the key system components are no longer hosted on a single machine.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Each function is now likely to have been designed as an Internet service that runs on multiple virtualized systems.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] The applications themselves are very likely to be moving from one system to another to meet service-level objectives and deal with momentary outages.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Applications themselves are becoming increasingly difficult to manage as they move toward highly distributed, multi-tier, multi-element constructs that in many cases rely on application development frameworks such as .NET or Java.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] The APM Conceptual Framework was designed to help prioritize an approach on what to focus on first for quick implementation and overall understanding of the five-dimensional APM model.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] The framework slide outlines three areas of focus for each dimension and describes their potential benefits.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Measuring the transit of traffic from user request to data and back again is part of capturing the end-user experience (EUE).
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] The outcome of this measuring is referred to as Real-time Application monitoring (aka Top-Down monitoring), which has two components, passive and active.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Passive monitoring is usually an agentless appliance implemented using network port mirroring.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] A key feature to consider is the ability to support multi-component analytics (e.g., database, client/browser).
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Active monitoring, on the other hand, consists of synthetic probes and web robots predefined to report system availability and business transactions.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Active monitoring is a good complement to passive monitoring; together, these two components help provide visibility into application health during off-peak hours when transaction volume is low.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] When preparing to implement a runtime application architecture, it is necessary to ensure that up/down monitoring is in place for all nodes and servers within the environment (aka, bottom-up monitoring).
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] This helps lay the foundation for event correlation and provides the basis for a general understanding of how network topologies interact with application architectures.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Focus on user-defined transactions or the URL page definitions that have some meaning to the business community.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] For example, if there are 200 to 300 unique page definitions for a given application, group them into 8–12 high-level categories.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] This allows for meaningful SLA reports, and provides trending information on application performance from a business perspective: start with broad categories and refine them over time.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] For a deeper understanding, see Business transaction management.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Deep dive component monitoring (DDCM) requires an agent installation and is generally targeted at middleware, focusing on web, application, and messaging servers.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] It should provide a real-time view of the J2EE and .NET stacks, tying them back to the user-defined business transactions.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] A robust monitor shows a clear path from code execution (e.g., spring and struts) to the URL rendered, and finally to the user request.
[src:apdex-score/application-performance-management] Since DDCM is closely related to the second dimension in the APM model, most products in this field also provide application discovery dependency mapping (ADDM) as part of their offering.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Latency is physically a consequence of the limited velocity at which any physical interaction can propagate.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] The magnitude of this velocity is always less than or equal to the speed of light.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Therefore, every physical system with any physical separation (distance) between cause and effect will experience some sort of latency, regardless of the nature of the stimulation to which it has been exposed.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] The precise definition of latency depends on the system being observed or the nature of the simulation.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] In communications, the lower limit of latency is determined by the medium being used to transfer information.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] In reliable two-way communication systems, latency limits the maximum rate at which information can be transmitted, as there is often a limit on the amount of information that is in-flight at any given moment.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Perceptible latency has a strong effect on user satisfaction and usability in the field of human–machine interaction.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Online games are sensitive to latency (lag), since fast response times to new events occurring during a game session are rewarded while slow response times may carry penalties.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Due to a delay in transmission of game events, a player with a high-latency internet connection may show slow responses in spite of appropriate reaction time.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] This gives players with low-latency connections a technical advantage.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Trading using computers has developed to the point where millisecond improvements in network speeds offer a competitive advantage for financial institutions.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] However, in a non-trivial network, a typical packet will be forwarded over multiple links and gateways, each of which will not begin to forward the packet until it has been completely received.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] In such a network, the minimal latency is the sum of the transmission delay of each link, plus the forwarding latency of each gateway.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] In practice, minimal latency also includes queuing and processing delays.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Queuing delay occurs when a gateway receives multiple packets from different sources heading toward the same destination.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Since typically only one packet can be transmitted at a time, some of the packets must queue for transmission, incurring additional delay.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Processing delays are incurred while a gateway determines what to do with a newly received packet.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Bufferbloat can also cause increased latency that is an order of magnitude or more.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] The combination of propagation, serialization, queuing, and processing delays often produces a complex and variable network latency profile.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Latency limits total throughput in reliable two-way communication systems as described by the bandwidth-delay product.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Latency in optical fiber is largely a function of the speed of light.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] This would equate to a latency of 3.33 μs for every kilometer of path length.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] The index of refraction of most fiber optic cables is about 1.5, meaning that light travels about 1.5 times as fast in a vacuum as it does in the cable.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] This works out to about 5.0 μs of latency for every kilometer.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] In shorter metro networks, higher latency can be experienced due to extra distance in building risers and cross-connects.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] To calculate the latency of a connection, one has to know the distance traveled by the fiber, which is rarely a straight line, since it has to traverse geographic contours and obstacles, such as roads and railway tracks, as well as other rights-of-way.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Due to imperfections in the fiber, light degrades as it is transmitted through it.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] For distances of greater than 100 kilometers, amplifiers or regenerators are deployed.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Latency introduced by these components needs to be taken into account.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Low Earth orbit is sometimes used to cut this delay, at the expense of more complicated satellite tracking on the ground and requiring more satellites in the satellite constellation to ensure continuous coverage.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Audio latency is the delay between when an audio signal enters and when it emerges from a system.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Potential contributors to latency in an audio system include analog-to-digital conversion, buffering, digital signal processing, transmission time, digital-to-analog conversion and the speed of sound in air.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Video latency refers to the degree of delay between the time a transfer of a video stream is requested and the actual time that transfer begins.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Networks that exhibit relatively small delays are known as low-latency networks, while their counterparts are known as high-latency networks.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Any individual workflow within a system of workflows can be subject to some type of operational latency.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] It may even be the case that an individual system may have more than one type of latency, depending on the type of participant or goal-seeking behavior.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] This is best illustrated by the following two examples involving air travel.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] From the point of view of a passenger, latency can be described as follows.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Suppose John Doe flies from London to New York.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] The latency of his trip is the time it takes him to go from his house in England to the hotel he is staying at in New York.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] This is independent of the throughput of the London-New York air link, whether there were 100 passengers a day making the trip or 10000, the latency of the trip would remain the same.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] From the point of view of flight operations personnel, latency can be entirely different.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Consider the staff at the London and New York airports.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Only a limited number of planes are able to make the transatlantic journey, so when one lands, they must prepare it for the return trip as quickly as possible.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] However, cleaning, refueling and loading the cargo can be done at the same time.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Passengers can only be loaded after cleaning is complete.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] The people involved in the turnaround are interested only in the time it takes for their individual tasks.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] When all of the tasks are done at the same time, however, it is possible to reduce the latency to the length of the longest task.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] If some steps have prerequisites, it becomes more difficult to perform all steps in parallel.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] In the example above, the requirement to clean the plane before loading passengers results in a minimum latency longer than any single task.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Any mechanical process encounters limitations modeled by Newtonian physics.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] The behavior of disk drives provides an example of mechanical latency.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Here, it is the time seek time for the actuator arm to be positioned above the appropriate track and then rotational latency for the data encoded on a platter to rotate from its current position to a position under the disk read-and-write head.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Computers run instructions in the context of a process.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] In the context of computer multitasking, the execution of the process can be postponed if other processes are also executing.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] In addition, the operating system can schedule when to perform the action that the process is commanding.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] For example, suppose a process commands that a computer card's voltage output be set high-low-high-low and so on at a rate of 1000 Hz.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] The operating system schedules the process for each transition (high-low or low-high) based on a hardware clock, such as the High Precision Event Timer.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] The latency is the delay between the events generated by the hardware clock and the actual transitions of voltage from high to low or low to high.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Many desktop operating systems have performance limitations that create additional latency.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] The problem may be mitigated with real-time extensions and patches such as PREEMPT RT.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] On embedded systems, the real-time execution of instructions is often supported by a real-time operating system.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Note that in software systems, benchmarking against *average* and *median* latency can be misleading because a few outliers can distort them.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Instead, software architects and software developers should use "99th percentile".
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] In simulation applications, latency refers to the time delay, often measured in milliseconds, between initial input and output clearly discernible to the simulator trainee or simulator subject.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Latency is sometimes also called *transport delay*.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] Some authorities distinguish between latency and transport delay by using the term *latency* in the sense of the extra time delay of a system over and above the reaction time of the vehicle being simulated, but this requires detailed knowledge of the vehicle dynamics and can be controversial.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] In simulators with both visual and motion systems, it is particularly important that the latency of the motion system not be greater than of the visual system, or symptoms of simulator sickness may result.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] This is because, in the real world, motion cues are those of acceleration and are quickly transmitted to the brain, typically in less than 50 milliseconds; this is followed some milliseconds later by a perception of change in the visual scene.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] The visual scene change is essentially one of change of perspective or displacement of objects, such as the horizon, which takes some time to build up to discernible amounts after the initial acceleration that caused the displacement.
[src:apdex-score/latency-engineering] A simulator should, therefore, reflect the real-world situation by ensuring that the motion latency is equal to or less than that of the visual system and not the other way round.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] This definition has been adopted in 2016 by the International Telecommunication Union in Recommendation ITU-T P.10/G.100.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] Before, various definitions of QoE had existed in the domain, with the above-mentioned definition now finding wide acceptance in the community.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] QoE has historically emerged from Quality of Service (QoS), which attempts to objectively measure service parameters (such as packet loss rates or average throughput).
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] QoS measurement is most of the time not related to a customer, but to the media or network itself.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] QoE however is a purely subjective measure from the user's perspective of the overall quality of the service provided, by capturing people's aesthetic and hedonic needs.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] QoE is a blueprint of all human subjective and objective quality needs and experiences arising from the interaction of a person with technology and with business entities in a particular context.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] Although QoE is perceived as subjective, it is an important measure that counts for customers of a service.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] Being able to measure it in a controlled manner helps operators understand what may be wrong with their services and how to improve them.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] QoE aims at taking into consideration every factor that contributes to a user's perceived quality of a system or service.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] This includes system, human and contextual factors.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] Studies in the field of QoE have typically focused on system factors, primarily due to its origin in the QoS and network engineering domains.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] Through the use of dedicated test laboratories, the context is often sought to be kept constant.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] QoE is strongly related to but different from the field of User Experience (UX), which also focuses on users' experiences with services.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] Historically, QoE has emerged from telecommunication research, while UX has its roots in Human–Computer Interaction.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] Both fields can be considered multi-disciplinary.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] In contrast to UX, the goal of improving QoE for users was more strongly motivated by economic needs.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] As a measure of the end-to-end performance at the service level from the user's perspective, QoE is an important metric for the design of systems and engineering processes.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] This is particularly relevant for video services because – due to their high traffic demands –, bad network performance may highly affect the user's experience.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] So, when designing systems, the expected output, i.e. the expected QoE, is often taken into account – also as a system output metric and optimization goal.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] To measure this level of QoE, human ratings can be used.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] The mean opinion score (MOS) is a widely used measure for assessing the quality of media signals.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] It is a limited form of QoE measurement, relating to a specific media type, in a controlled environment and without explicitly taking into account user expectations.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] The MOS as an indicator of experienced quality has been used for audio and speech communication, as well as for the assessment of quality of Internet video, television and other multimedia signals, and web browsing.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] Due to inherent limitations in measuring QoE in a single scalar value, the usefulness of the MOS is often debated.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] Subjective quality evaluation requires a lot of human resources, establishing it as a time-consuming process.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] Objective evaluation methods can provide quality results faster, but require dedicated computing resources.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] Since such instrumental video quality algorithms are often developed based on a limited set of subjective data, their QoE prediction accuracy may be low when compared to human ratings.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] QoE metrics are often measured at the end devices and can conceptually be seen as the remaining quality after the distortion introduced during the preparation of the content and the delivery through the network, until it reaches the decoder at the end device.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] There are several elements in the media preparation and delivery chain, and some of them may introduce distortion.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] This causes degradation of the content, and several elements in this chain can be considered as "QoE-relevant" for the offered services.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] The causes of degradation are applicable for any multimedia service, that is, not exclusive to video or speech.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] Typical degradations occur at the encoding system (compression degradation), transport network, access network (e.g., packet loss or packet delay), home network (e.g.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] WiFi performance) and end device (e.g. decoding performance).
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] Several QoE-centric network management and bandwidth management solutions have been proposed, which aim to improve the QoE delivered to the end-users.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] When managing a network, QoE fairness may be taken into account in order to keep the users sufficiently satisfied (i.e., high QoE) in a fair manner.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] From a QoE perspective, network resources and multimedia services should be managed in order to guarantee specific QoE levels instead of classical QoS parameters, which are unable to reflect the actual delivered QoE.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] A pure QoE-centric management is challenged by the nature of the Internet itself, as the Internet protocols and architecture were not originally designed to support today's complex and high demanding multimedia services.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] As an example for an implementation of QoE management, network nodes can become QoE-aware by estimating the status of the multimedia service as perceived by the end-users.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] This information can then be used to improve the delivery of the multimedia service over the network and proactively improve the users' QoE.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] This can be achieved, for example, via traffic shaping.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] QoE management gives the service provider and network operator the capability to minimize storage and network resources by allocating only the resources that are sufficient to maintain a specific level of user satisfaction.
[src:apdex-score/quality-of-experience] As it may involve limiting resources for some users or services in order to increase the overall network performance and QoE, the practice of QoE management requires that net neutrality regulations are considered.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] In technology, **response time** is the time a system or functional unit takes to react to a given input.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] In computing, the responsiveness of a service, how long a system takes to respond to a request for service, is measured through the response time.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] That service can be anything from a memory fetch, to a disk IO, to a complex database query, or loading a full web page.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] Ignoring transmission time for a moment, the response time is the sum of the service time and wait time.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] The service time is the time it takes to do the work you requested.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] For a given request the service time varies little as the workload increases – to do X amount of work it always takes X amount of time.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] The wait time is how long the request had to wait in a queue before being serviced and it varies from zero, when no waiting is required, to a large multiple of the service time, as many requests are already in the queue and have to be serviced first.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] With basic queueing theory math you can calculate how the average wait time increases as the device providing the service goes from 0-100% busy.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] As the device becomes busier, the average wait time increases in a non-linear fashion.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] The busier the device is, the more dramatic the response time increases will seem as you approach 100% busy; all of that increase is caused by increases in wait time, which is the result of all the requests waiting in queue that have to run first.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] Transmission time gets added to response time when your request and the resulting response has to travel over a network and it can be very significant.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] Transmission time can include propagation delays due to distance (the speed of light is finite), delays due to transmission errors, and data communication bandwidth limits (especially at the last mile) slowing the transmission speed of the request or the reply.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] Developers can reduce the response time of a system (for end users or not) using program optimization techniques.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] In real-time systems the response time of a task or thread is defined as the time elapsed between the dispatch (time when task is ready to execute) to the time when it finishes its job (one dispatch).
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] Response time is different from WCET which is the maximum time the task would take if it were to execute without interference.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] It is also different from deadline which is the length of time during which the task's output would be valid in the context of the specific system.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] And it has a relation to the TTFB, which is the time between the dispatch and the time when the response starts.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] Response time is the amount of time a pixel in a display takes to change.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] Lower numbers mean faster transitions and therefore fewer visible image artifacts.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] Display monitors with long response times would create display motion blur around moving objects, making them unacceptable for rapidly moving images.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] Response times are usually measured from grey-to-grey transitions, based on a VESA industry standard from the 10% to the 90% points in the pixel response curve.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] In fast paced competitive games such as Counter-Strike, the response time of a display is crucial for optimal performance.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] Displays that have a lower response time are more responsive to player input and produce less visual errors when displaying a rapidly changing image, making low response time important for competitive gaming.
[src:apdex-score/response-time-technology] Most modern monitors that are marketed for gaming have a response time of 1ms, although it is not uncommon to see <1ms response time in high end monitors, and >1ms response time on less expensive monitors or monitors that have a higher resolution.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] According to Nielsen Norman Group, 'user experience' includes all the aspects of the interaction between the end-user with the company, its services, and its products.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] The international standard on *ergonomics of human-system interaction*, ISO 9241, defines user experience as a "user's perceptions and responses that result from the use and/or anticipated use of a system, product or service".
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] According to the ISO definition, user experience includes all the users' emotions, beliefs, preferences, perceptions, physical and psychological responses, behaviors, and accomplishments that occur before, during, and after use.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] The ISO also lists three factors that influence user experience: the system, the user, and the context of use.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Note 3 of the standard hints that usability addresses aspects of user experience, e.g., "usability criteria can be used to assess aspects of user experience".
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] The standard does not go further in clarifying the relation between user experience and usability.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Clearly, the two are overlapping concepts, with usability including pragmatic aspects (getting a task done) and user experience focusing on users' feelings stemming from both pragmatic and hedonic aspects of the system.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Many practitioners use the terms interchangeably.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] The term "usability" pre-dates the term "user experience".
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Part of the reason the terms are often used interchangeably is that, as a practical matter, a user will, at a minimum, require sufficient usability to accomplish a task, while the feelings of the user may be less important, even to the user themselves.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Since usability is about getting a task done, aspects of user experience like information architecture and user interface can help or hinder a user's experience.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] If a website has "bad" information architecture and a user has a difficult time finding what they are looking for, then the user will not have an effective, efficient, and satisfying search.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] In addition to the ISO standard, there exist several other definitions for user experience.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Some of them have been studied by various researchers.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Early developments in user experience can be traced back to the Machine Age, which includes the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Frederick Winslow Taylor and Henry Ford explored ways to make human labor more efficient and productive.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Taylor's research into the efficiency of interactions between workers and their tools is the earliest example that resembles today's user experience fundamentals.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] The term *user experience* was brought to wider knowledge by Donald Norman in the mid-1990s.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] He never intended the term "user experience" to be applied only to the affective aspects of usage.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] A review of his earlier work suggests that the term "user experience" was used to signal a shift to include affective factors, along with the pre-requisite behavioral concerns, which had been traditionally considered in the field.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Many usability practitioners continue to research and attend to affective factors associated with end-users, and have been doing so for years, long before the term "user experience" was introduced in the mid-1990s.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] In an interview in 2007, Norman discusses the widespread use of the term "user experience" and its imprecise meaning as a consequence thereof.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] In website design, it was important to combine the interests of different stakeholders: marketing, branding, visual design, and usability.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Marketing and branding people needed to enter the interactive world where usability was important.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Usability people needed to take marketing, branding, and aesthetic needs into account when designing websites.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] User experience provided a platform to cover the interests of all stakeholders: making websites easy to use, valuable, and effective for visitors.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] This is why several early user experience publications focus on website user experience.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] The field of user experience represents an expansion and extension of the field of usability to include the holistic perspective of how a person feels about using a system.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] The focus is on pleasure and value as well as on performance.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] The exact definition, framework, and elements of user experience are still evolving.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] User experience of an interactive product or a website is usually measured by a number of methods, including questionnaires, focus groups, observed usability tests, user journey mapping and other methods.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] A freely available questionnaire (available in several languages) is the User Experience Questionnaire (UEQ).
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] The development and validation of this questionnaire is described in a computer science essay published in 2008.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Higher levels of user experience have been linked to increased effectiveness of digital health interventions targeting improvements in physical activity, nutrition, mental health and smoking.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Google Ngram Viewer shows wide use of the term starting in the 1930s.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] "He suggested that more follow-up in the field would be welcomed by the user, and would be a means of incorporating the results of the user's experience into the design of new machines." Use of the term in relation to computer software also pre-dates Norman.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Many factors can influence a user's experience with a system.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] To address the variety, factors influencing user experience have been classified into three main categories: the user's state and previous experience, system properties, and the usage context (situation).
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Understanding representative users, working environments, interactions, and emotional reactions helps in designing the system during User experience design.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] The overall user experience is not simply a sum of smaller interaction experiences, because some experiences are more salient than others.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Overall user experience is also influenced by factors outside the actual interaction episode: brand, pricing, friends' opinions, reports in the media, etc.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] One branch of user experience research focuses on emotions.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] This includes momentary experiences during interaction: designing effective interaction and evaluating emotions.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Another branch is interested in understanding the long-term relationship between user experience and product appreciation.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] The industry sees a good overall user experience with a company's products as critical for securing brand loyalty and enhancing the growth of the customer base.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] All temporal levels of user experience (momentary, episodic, and long-term) are important, but the methods to design and evaluate these levels can be very different.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] While user experience has become an essential part of design and product development, it has also attracted criticism and ethical scrutiny.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Focusing on user satisfaction and business goals may lead to harmful design choices, unintentional accessibility gaps, or user manipulation.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] These conflicts suggest that UX has room to become a more responsible and inclusive practice.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] One major critique of UX is the conflict between designing for user benefit and designing for business objectives.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] UX decisions are often shaped by financial incentives rather than users’ well-being.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] This leads to design choices that prioritize growth over ethics, for example, features that encourage excessive screen time, collect unnecessary personal data (also known as *privacy zuckering*), or make it difficult for users to unsubscribe from services (also known as *forced continuity*).
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] While trying to increase profits, it may actually increase economic harm and reduce market efficiency.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Critics argue that such practices compromise the foundational goal of UX, which is to improve the user's experience, not exploit it.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Companies can be held accountable for their design choices by prioritizing user interests.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] For instance, ensuring price transparency helps users make informed decisions.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Organizations can also align design decisions with user well-being by evaluating qualitative outcomes, like how a product contributes to users’ happiness or mental health, instead of relying solely on engagement metrics.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] By making business success dependent on user trust and satisfaction, rather than engagement metrics alone, organizations can create sustainable products that support both profitability and user well-being.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Another major ethical concern in UX is the use of dark patterns, interface designs that intentionally mislead or manipulate users into taking actions they might not otherwise choose.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Examples include use of checkboxes to opt out rather than opt in (double negatives), confusing cancellation processes, or “confirm” buttons that lead to unintended purchases.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Scholars from Princeton and Purdue University have argued that dark patterns represent a misuse of UX principles, using psychological insights and interface design against user interests.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] One proposed solution to the problem of dark patterns is to focus on how to distinguish manipulative patterns from legitimate persuasion.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] For example, researchers at Princeton suggest using guidelines to evaluate when a design crosses the line into manipulation.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Researchers from Purdue University instead argue that ethical awareness cannot rely solely on codes of conduct but should instead focus on the designer’s intent, judgment, and ongoing responsibility.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Another area of criticism concerns accessibility and inclusivity in UX design.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Although improving usability is a central aim of UX, many products and services continue to overlook the needs of people with disabilities, older users, or those from different cultural and linguistic backgrounds.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] This exclusion can occur due to implicit bias in design teams, lack of diverse user testing, or assumptions about “average” users.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] To address these gaps, experts recommend adopting inclusive design principles throughout the development process.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] This includes conducting accessibility audits, following the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG), and involving users with disabilities in usability testing to ensure products meet real-world needs.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Expanding user research to include diverse groups can also uncover assumptions and biases early.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Additionally, ongoing education about unconscious bias for design teams can help create products that reflect a broader range of user experiences.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] Developer experience (DX) is a user experience from a developer's point of view.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] It is defined by the tools, processes, and software that a developer uses when interacting with a product or system while in the process of producing another one, such as in software development.
[src:apdex-score/user-experience] DX has had increased attention paid to it, especially in businesses that primarily offer software as a service to other businesses, where ease of use is a key differentiator in the market.
